    <node id="cxl_1_0">
      <data key="d6">protocol_revision</data>
      <data key="d0">CXL 1.0 / 1.1 Specification</data>
      <data key="d7">Initial release (March 2019). Direct-attached device, 32 GT/s link rate, 68-byte flit mode, single-node coherent interconnect with load/store semantics and hardware-enforced cache coherence. CXL 1.1 (June 2019) added compliance and interoperability.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"release_date": "March 2019 (1.0) / June 2019 (1.1)", "max_link_rate": "32 GT/s", "flit_size": "68 byte", "key_feature": "single-node coherent interconnect"}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Revision History table; CXL 4.0 Webinar timeline</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">cxl 1.0 / 1.1 specification</data>
    </node>
    <node id="cxl_2_0">
      <data key="d6">protocol_revision</data>
      <data key="d0">CXL 2.0 Specification</data>
      <data key="d7">Released October 2020. Added single-level switching, memory pooling with MLDs, managed hot-plug, persistent memory support, Global Persistent Flush (GPF), link-level encryption (CXL IDE), Fabric Manager API, and telemetry. Fully backward compatible with CXL 1.1/1.0.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"release_date": "October 26, 2020", "max_link_rate": "32 GT/s", "key_features": ["Switch/Memory Pooling", "Hot-Plug", "Persistent memory", "CXL IDE", "Fabric Manager"]}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Revision History; CXL 4.0 Webinar</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">cxl 2.0 specification</data>
    </node>
    <node id="cxl_3_0">
      <data key="d6">protocol_revision</data>
      <data key="d0">CXL 3.0 Specification</data>
      <data key="d7">Released August 2022. Doubled bandwidth to 64 GT/s using PAM-4 signaling on PCIe 6.0 PHY. Introduced multi-level switching up to 4K ports, Port-Based Routing (PBR) fabric, Back-Invalidate Snoop (BISnp), HDM-DB coherence, direct peer-to-peer to HDM memory, shared memory across virtual hierarchies, and 256B flit format.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"release_date": "August 1, 2022", "max_link_rate": "64 GT/s", "signaling": "PAM-4", "pcie_phy": "PCIe 6.0", "flit_size": "256 byte", "max_ports": "4K"}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Section 1.4.1 overview; Revision History</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">cxl 3.0 specification</data>
    </node>
    <node id="cxl_3_1">
      <data key="d6">protocol_revision</data>
      <data key="d0">CXL 3.1 Specification</data>
      <data key="d7">Released November 2023. Added CXL Fabric capabilities, Global Integrated Memory (GIM), Trusted-Execution-Environment (TEE) Security Protocol (TSP), and host-to-host communication.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"release_date": "November 2023", "max_link_rate": "64 GT/s", "key_features": ["CXL Fabric", "TSP", "GIM"]}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">CXL 4.0 Webinar timeline slide</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">cxl 3.1 specification</data>
    </node>
    <node id="cxl_3_2">
      <data key="d6">protocol_revision</data>
      <data key="d0">CXL 3.2 Specification</data>
      <data key="d7">Released December 2024. Security, compliance, and CXL Memory Device enhancements; memory expander enhancements (up to 32-bit metadata, RAS capability).</data>
      <data key="d10">{"release_date": "December 2024", "max_link_rate": "64 GT/s", "key_features": ["Security &amp; Compliance", "Memory RAS enhancements"]}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">CXL 4.0 Webinar timeline slide</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">cxl 3.2 specification</data>
    </node>
    <node id="cxl_4_0">
      <data key="d6">protocol_revision</data>
      <data key="d0">CXL 4.0 Specification</data>
      <data key="d7">Released November 2025 (evaluation copy dated August 13, 2025; version 1.0). Doubles data rate to 128 GT/s using PCIe 7.0 Base Specification PHY; uses same 256B flit arrangement, FEC, and CRC as CXL 3.0. Introduces CXL Bundled Ports for logical aggregation of multiple CXL ports (Type 1/2/3 accelerators), native x2 width support, up to 4 retimers for channel extension, optical link support via PCIe 7.0, and memory RAS enhancements (granular CVME events, host-initiated Post Package Repair, flexible memory sparing).</data>
      <data key="d10">{"release_date": "November 2025", "revision": "4.0, Version 1.0", "max_link_rate": "128 GT/s", "pcie_phy": "PCIe 7.0", "flit_size": "256 byte (with Latency-Optimized variant)", "key_features": ["128 GT/s bandwidth", "Bundled Ports", "Native x2 width", "4 Retimers", "Optical support", "Memory RAS: PPR + sparing"], "backward_compatible": "CXL 3.x, 2.0, 1.1, 1.0"}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Section 1.4.1; CXL 4.0 Webinar feature slides</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">cxl 4.0 specification</data>
    </node>
    <node id="cxl_io">
      <data key="d6">sub_protocol</data>
      <data key="d0">CXL.io</data>
      <data key="d7">PCIe-based non-coherent I/O protocol with enhancements for accelerator support. Required for all CXL implementations; used for discovery, enumeration, configuration, error reporting, interrupts, DMA, ATS, and peer-to-peer access to CXL memory via Unordered I/O (UIO).</data>
      <data key="d10">{"base": "PCIe Transaction Layer", "required": "yes (always mandatory)", "use_cases": ["discovery", "enumeration", "error reporting", "HPA lookup", "P2P via UIO"]}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Terminology Table 1-1; Section 1.4.1; Section 3.1</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">cxl.io</data>
    </node>
    <node id="cxl_cache">
      <data key="d6">sub_protocol</data>
      <data key="d0">CXL.cache</data>
      <data key="d7">Agent coherency protocol that supports device caching of host memory. Optional protocol for devices that need fully coherent caches (Type 1 and Type 2 devices). Uses D2H Request, D2H Response, D2H Data, H2D Request, H2D Response, H2D Data channels.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"required": "optional (Type 1, Type 2)", "channels": ["D2H Request", "D2H Response", "D2H Data", "H2D Request", "H2D Response", "H2D Data"], "purpose": "device caches host memory coherently"}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Terminology Table 1-1; Section 3.2</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">cxl.cache</data>
    </node>
    <node id="cxl_mem">
      <data key="d6">sub_protocol</data>
      <data key="d0">CXL.mem</data>
      <data key="d7">Memory access protocol that supports device-attached memory (HDM — Host-managed Device Memory). Used by Type 2 and Type 3 devices. Introduced Back-Invalidate Snoop (BISnp) channel in CXL 3.0 for HDM-DB coherence, and QoS Telemetry with 2-bit DevLoad field. Supports M2S Request, M2S RwD, S2M NDR, S2M DRS, S2M BISnp, M2S BIRsp.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"required": "optional (Type 2, Type 3)", "message_classes": ["M2S Req", "M2S RwD", "S2M NDR", "S2M DRS", "S2M BISnp", "M2S BIRsp"], "coherence_modes": ["HDM-H", "HDM-D", "HDM-DB"]}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Terminology Table 1-1; Section 3.3</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">cxl.mem</data>
    </node>
    <node id="cxl_type_1_device">
      <data key="d6">device_class</data>
      <data key="d0">CXL Type 1 Device</data>
      <data key="d7">Accelerator/caching device with fully coherent cache but no device-attached memory. Uses CXL.io + CXL.cache protocols. Example use cases: NIC atomics, PGAS NICs, Smart NICs, complex atomics. Supports producer-consumer models that don't work with standard PCIe ordering; cache size limited by host's snoop-filter capacity.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"protocols": ["CXL.io", "CXL.cache"], "has_memory": false, "has_cache": true, "example_devices": ["NIC atomics", "PGAS NIC", "Smart NIC"]}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Section 2.1 'CXL Type 1 Device'</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">cxl type 1 device</data>
    </node>
    <node id="cxl_type_2_device">
      <data key="d6">device_class</data>
      <data key="d0">CXL Type 2 Device</data>
      <data key="d7">Accelerator with device-attached memory that negotiates all three protocols (CXL.io, CXL.cache, CXL.mem). Device memory (DDR, HBM, GDDR) is exposed as Host-managed Device Memory (HDM-D or HDM-DB). Example: GPGPU, FPGA, dense-computation accelerators. Implements bias-based coherency (Host Bias vs Device Bias) for HDM-D; HDM-DB uses Back-Invalidate Snoop channel.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"protocols": ["CXL.io", "CXL.cache", "CXL.mem"], "has_memory": true, "has_cache": true, "memory_types": ["DDR", "HBM", "GDDR"], "coherence_modes": ["HDM-D (bias-based)", "HDM-DB (back-invalidate)"], "example_devices": ["GPU", "GPGPU", "FPGA"]}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Section 2.2 'CXL Type 2 Device'</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">cxl type 2 device</data>
    </node>
    <node id="cxl_type_3_device">
      <data key="d6">device_class</data>
      <data key="d0">CXL Type 3 Device</data>
      <data key="d7">Memory expander/memory buffer. Supports CXL.io + CXL.mem protocols (no CXL.cache). Primary use: passive memory expansion (HDM-H) where device does not manipulate memory content while exposed to host. HDM-DB variant supports accelerator-like behavior and peer UIO access. Can be partitioned into up to 16 Logical Devices (MLD). Supports memory pooling, memory sharing (FAM/G-FAM), and 2LM (two-level memory) tiering.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"protocols": ["CXL.io", "CXL.mem"], "has_memory": true, "has_cache": false, "coherence_modes": ["HDM-H (Host-only)", "HDM-DB"], "variants": ["SLD", "MLD (up to 16 LDs)", "MH-SLD", "MH-MLD", "G-FAM (GFD)", "DCD"]}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Section 2.3 'CXL Type 3 Device'; Section 2.4 MLD</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">cxl type 3 device</data>
    </node>
    <node id="flex_bus">
      <data key="d6">physical_interface</data>
      <data key="d0">Flex Bus</data>
      <data key="d7">A flexible high-speed port that can be dynamically configured to support either native PCIe protocol or CXL over a high-bandwidth off-package link. Selection occurs during link training via alternate protocol negotiation. Uses PCIe electricals, compatible with PCIe retimers and form factors. Supports x16, x8, x4, x2, x1 link widths; signaling rates 8/16/32/64/128 GT/s.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"signaling_rates": "8/16/32/64/128 GT/s", "link_widths": "x16/x8/x4/x2/x1", "modes": ["PCIe mode", "CXL mode (Flex Bus.CXL)"]}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Section 1.4.2 'Flex Bus'; Section 1.5</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">flex bus</data>
    </node>
    <node id="bundled_port">
      <data key="d6">feature</data>
      <data key="d0">CXL Bundled Port (BPD)</data>
      <data key="d7">CXL 4.0 feature: logical aggregation of multiple CXL ports of an accelerator device (Type 1, Type 2, Type 3 non-memory). A Bundle exposes at least one standard full-capability Port and any number of Streamlined Ports. Streamlined Ports are area/power-optimized for data bandwidth expansion, 256B Flit mode only, optimized for UIO. Each port exposes an SLD-B (Single Logical Device of a Bundle).</data>
      <data key="d10">{"introduced_in": "CXL 4.0", "components": ["Standard Port", "Streamlined Port", "SLD-B"], "applicable_devices": ["Type 1", "Type 2", "Type 3 accelerator (non-memory)"]}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Section 1.4.1 paragraph on CXL 4.0; Section 2.10; Webinar slides 16-20</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">cxl bundled port (bpd)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="hdm">
      <data key="d6">concept</data>
      <data key="d0">Host-managed Device Memory (HDM)</data>
      <data key="d7">Device memory exposed to the host and managed by the host coherence domain. Three variants: HDM-H (Host-only coherent, Type 3 memory expander), HDM-D (Device coherent using CXL.cache bias model), HDM-DB (Device coherent using Back-Invalidate Snoop on CXL.mem; required for 256B flit devices).</data>
      <data key="d10">{"variants": ["HDM-H", "HDM-D", "HDM-DB"]}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Chapter 2.0 introduction; Section 2.2</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">host-managed device memory (hdm)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="mld">
      <data key="d6">feature</data>
      <data key="d0">Multi-Logical Device (MLD)</data>
      <data key="d7">Type 3 device partitioned into up to 16 isolated Logical Devices (LDs), each identified by a 16-bit LD-ID. Each LD appears as a Type 3 device to its bound Virtual Hierarchy (VH). One LD is reserved for the Fabric Manager (FMLD, LD-ID FFFFh). Enables memory pooling.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"max_lds": 16, "introduced_in": "CXL 2.0"}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Section 2.4 'Multi Logical Device (MLD)'</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">multi-logical device (mld)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="g_fam">
      <data key="d6">feature</data>
      <data key="d0">Global FAM (G-FAM) / GFD</data>
      <data key="d7">Global Fabric-Attached Memory. Highly scalable form of FAM that presents HDM to hosts without using Logical Devices, instead using Port-Based Routing (PBR) with Source PID (SPID). G-FAM devices (GFDs) support multiple host/peer interfaces on one or more links. Enables pooled or shared memory at fabric scale.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"introduced_in": "CXL 3.0", "routing": "Port-Based Routing (PBR)"}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Terminology Table; Section 2.4.3; Section 2.8</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">global fam (g-fam) / gfd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="fabric_manager">
      <data key="d6">concept</data>
      <data key="d0">Fabric Manager (FM)</data>
      <data key="d7">Entity separate from switch or host firmware that controls binding and management of pooled CXL ports and devices. Introduced in CXL 2.0. Standardized API for switch orchestration in CXL 3.0/3.1 fabrics. Fabric Manager API over MCTP Binding Specification DSP0234.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"introduced_in": "CXL 2.0", "api_spec": "DMTF DSP0234"}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Terminology Table; Reference Documents Table 1-2</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">fabric manager (fm)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="cxl_ide">
      <data key="d6">feature</data>
      <data key="d0">CXL Integrity and Data Encryption (CXL IDE)</data>
      <data key="d7">Link-level encryption scheme used for securing CXL protocol flits across the link. Uses AES-GCM per NIST SP 800-38D. Introduced in CXL 2.0.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"introduced_in": "CXL 2.0", "cipher": "AES-GCM (NIST SP 800-38D)"}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Chapter 11.0 CXL Security; Revision History</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">cxl integrity and data encryption (cxl ide)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="tsp">
      <data key="d6">feature</data>
      <data key="d0">TEE Security Protocol (TSP)</data>
      <data key="d7">CXL-defined TEE Security Protocol. Collection of requirements and interfaces that allow memory devices to be utilized for confidential computing. Leverages PCI-SIG TDISP, SPDM, and DSM (Device Security Manager) / TSM (TEE Security Manager).</data>
      <data key="d10">{"introduced_in": "CXL 3.1", "related_standards": ["PCI-SIG TDISP", "DMTF SPDM DSP0274"]}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Terminology Table (TSP, TSM, DSM, TDISP entries)</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">tee security protocol (tsp)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="pcie_7_0">
      <data key="d6">related_standard</data>
      <data key="d0">PCI Express Base Specification 7.0</data>
      <data key="d7">PCIe Base Specification Revision 7.0. Provides the PHY used by CXL 4.0 at 128 GT/s, including its FEC, CRC, and optical link support. Published by PCI-SIG.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"organization": "PCI-SIG", "rate": "128 GT/s", "used_by": "CXL 4.0"}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Reference Documents Table 1-2; CXL 4.0 Webinar</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">pci express base specification 7.0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="pcie_6_0">
      <data key="d6">related_standard</data>
      <data key="d0">PCI Express 6.0</data>
      <data key="d7">PCIe 6.0 provides the 64 GT/s PAM-4 PHY leveraged by CXL 3.0/3.1/3.2.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"organization": "PCI-SIG", "rate": "64 GT/s", "used_by": "CXL 3.x"}</data>
      <data key="d8">0.95</data>
      <data key="d9">CXL 3.0 description in Section 1.4.1 references PCIe Base PHY; PCIe 6.0 is the industry standard at 64 GT/s</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">pci express 6.0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="pci_sig">
      <data key="d6">organization</data>
      <data key="d0">PCI-SIG</data>
      <data key="d7">Standards organization that publishes the PCI Express Base Specification and related specifications (CEM, ATS, DOE, AER, TDISP). CXL is built on top of PCIe electricals and reuses much of the PCIe protocol stack.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"website": "www.pcisig.com"}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Reference Documents Table 1-2</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">pci-sig</data>
    </node>
    <node id="dmtf">
      <data key="d6">organization</data>
      <data key="d0">DMTF (Distributed Management Task Force)</data>
      <data key="d7">Standards body for DSP0234 (Fabric Manager API over MCTP), DSP0236 (MCTP Base), DSP0274 (SPDM), DSP0281 (CXL Type 3 CCI over MCTP). CXL references numerous DMTF specifications for management and security.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"website": "www.dmtf.org"}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Reference Documents Table 1-2 (Sheet 1-2)</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">dmtf (distributed management task force)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="uefi_forum">
      <data key="d6">organization</data>
      <data key="d0">UEFI Forum</data>
      <data key="d7">Publishes ACPI Specification (6.5+), CDAT Specification, and UEFI Specification, all referenced by CXL for coherent device attribute tables, memory affinity structures, and firmware interfaces.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"website": "www.uefi.org"}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Reference Documents Table 1-2</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">uefi forum</data>
    </node>
    <node id="jedec">
      <data key="d6">organization</data>
      <data key="d0">JEDEC</data>
      <data key="d7">Publishes DDR5 Specification (JESD79-5), referenced by CXL for memory device specifications.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"website": "www.jedec.org"}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Reference Documents Table 1-2</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">jedec</data>
    </node>
    <node id="xconn">
      <data key="d6">company</data>
      <data key="d0">Xconn Technologies</data>
      <data key="d7">CXL member; JP Jiang represents Xconn. Develops CXL switches for memory disaggregation and fabric topologies.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"role": "CXL switch silicon vendor"}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">CXL_Q2-2025-Webinar_FINAL.pdf panelist list</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">xconn technologies</data>
    </node>
    <node id="sap">
      <data key="d6">company</data>
      <data key="d0">SAP SE</data>
      <data key="d7">Enterprise software vendor; collaborated with Intel on TPCC benchmark studies showing CXL-pooled memory works well for database workloads with negligible performance degradation even with switches.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"role": "software co-validator for CXL pooling"}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">CXL 4.0 Webinar slide 24 (Ecosystem Health)</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">sap se</data>
    </node>
    <node id="memory_pooling_usecase">
      <data key="d6">use_case</data>
      <data key="d0">Memory Pooling</data>
      <data key="d7">Data center use case where CXL-attached memory (Type 3 MLD or GFD) is disaggregated from compute and dynamically allocated across servers. Reduces memory stranding, improves utilization, lowers TCO. Microsoft Pond paper (ASPLOS 2023) showed 9% DRAM savings.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"enabled_by": ["CXL 2.0 MLD", "CXL 3.0 G-FAM"], "validated_by": ["Microsoft Pond", "SAP+Intel TPCC"]}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">CXL 4.0 Webinar challenge 3 slides; ecosystem health slide</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">memory pooling</data>
    </node>
    <node id="memory_sharing_usecase">
      <data key="d6">use_case</data>
      <data key="d0">Coherent Memory Sharing</data>
      <data key="d7">CXL 3.0+ use case where multiple hosts concurrently access a single HDM region (Shared FAM) with hardware-enforced coherence across copies in host caches. Enables collaborative processing and in-memory message passing across virtual hierarchies.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"enabled_by": ["CXL 3.0 BISnp", "Shared FAM"]}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Section 1.4.1 Figure 1-4; CXL Q2 2025 Webinar</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">coherent memory sharing</data>
    </node>
    <node id="accelerator_coherency_usecase">
      <data key="d6">use_case</data>
      <data key="d0">Accelerator Cache Coherency</data>
      <data key="d7">CXL enables accelerators (GPUs, FPGAs, NICs) to participate in host cache coherence via CXL.cache and to expose accelerator-local memory as HDM. Eliminates high-bandwidth copies between host and device memory that plague traditional PCIe-attached accelerators.</data>
      <data key="d10">{"enabled_by": ["CXL.cache", "CXL.mem HDM-D/HDM-DB"]}</data>
      <data key="d8">1.0</data>
      <data key="d9">Section 2.1, 2.2; CXL 4.0 Webinar Challenge 1</data>
      <data key="d4">15</data>
      <data key="d5">accelerator cache coherency</data>
    </node>
    <node id="composable_fabric_usecase">
      <data key="d6">use_case</data>
      <data key="d0">Composable Disaggregated Fabric</data>
